✅ What are layout.js and template.js in the Next.js App Router?
In the Next.js App Router (app/ directory), both layout.js and template.js define shared UI wrappers for routes.
The key difference is whether the UI is preserved or re‑created during navigation.

🔹 layout.js
👉 What it is
layout.js defines a persistent layout that wraps pages and nested routes inside a folder.
✅ Key Characteristics
	• Persists across route navigation
	• Does NOT re‑mount when moving between child routes
	• Preserves state
	• Server Component by default
	• Must render {children}
📁 Example
app/dashboard/
 ├── layout.js
 ├── page.js
 └── settings/page.js
✅ Example Code

export default function DashboardLayout({ children }) {
  return (
    <div>
      <Sidebar />
      <main>{children}</main>
    </div>
  );
}
``
✅ Sidebar stays mounted
✅ Only page content changes
✅ Best Use Cases
	• App shell (header, footer)
	• Sidebar navigation
	• Authentication wrappers
	• Global providers (theme, auth)

🔹 template.js
👉 What it is
template.js is similar to layout.js but re‑mounts on every navigation.
✅ Key Characteristics
	• Re‑created on every route change
	• State is reset
	• Server Component by default
	• Must render {children}
✅ Example Code

export default function DashboardTemplate({ children }) {
  return <div className="fade-in">{children}</div>;
}
✅ Re‑triggers animations
✅ Clears state on navigation
✅ Best Use Cases
	• Page transition animations
	• Scroll reset behavior
	• UI that must restart on each navigation

⚖️ layout.js vs template.js
Aspect	layout.js	template.js
Persistence	✅ Yes	❌ No
Re‑mounts on navigation	❌ No	✅ Yes
State preserved	✅ Yes	❌ No
Performance	✅ Better	Slightly lower
Typical usage	App structure	Transitions / resets

🧠 Interview‑Ready 30‑Second Answer
	In the Next.js App Router, layout.js is used for persistent layouts that wrap routes and preserve state across navigation, such as headers or sidebars.
	template.js is similar but re‑mounts on every navigation, making it useful when UI state must reset, like animations or transitions.

✅ Rule of Thumb (Say This)
	• Need persistence? → layout.js ✅
	• Need reset on every navigation? → template.js ✅
